<activity><title>Volume of a Box</title>

<introduction><p> A paper company plans to make boxes without tops from sheets of cardboard 8 inches wide and 12 inches long. They will cut out four squares of side <m>x</m> inches from the corners of the sheet and fold up the edges.</p></introduction> 

            <commentary audience="instructor"><title>Note</title>
            <p>It is helpful to physically cut the corners from a sheet of paper or cardboard and turn up the edges to illustrate the box.</p></commentary>

<task><p> Write expressions in terms of  for the length, width, and height of the resulting box.</p>
    <p>Length:</p>
    <p>Width:</p>
    <p>Height:</p></task>                                                                     

<task><p>Write a formula for the volume <m>V</m> of the box as a function of <m>x</m>.</p></task>

<task><p>Use technology to graph your function for <m>-5 \le x \le 10</m>.</p></task>

<task><p>What are the largest and smallest reasonable values for <m>x</m> in this situation? Explain your answer.</p></task>

            <commentary audience="instructor"><title>Note</title>
            <p>Students may not understand what is asked in part (d), so you may want to make a table showing the length, width, and height of the box for various values of <m>x</m>.</p></commentary>

<task><p>Use your answer to part (d) to graph the function in a suitable window. Make a sketch of your graph, and label the scales on the axes.</p></task>

<task><p>Use your graph to find the value of <m>x</m> that will yield a box with maximum possible volume.</p>  

            <commentary audience="instructor"><title>Note</title>
            <p>Point out that (at this point) we don't have an algebraic method for solving cubic equations, so we use a graphical solution instead.</p></commentary>

  <p>Label the corresponding point on your graph.</p>
  <p>What is the maximum possible volume?</p>
  <p>What are the dimensions of the box with the largest possible volume?</p></task>
</activity>

<subsection><title>Check Your Understanding</title>
<p><ol>
<li><p>In part (e) of Activity 1, how many terms of the product are quadratic?  How many of the terms are cubic?</p></li>
<li><p>Explain the difference between the expressions <m>(a+b)^3</m> and <m>a^3+b^3</m>.</p></li>
<li><p>Compare the formulas for expanding <m>(a-b)^2</m> and <m>(a-b)^3</m>.</p></li>
<li><p>In Activity 3, why is the polynomial for the volume of the box cubic?  What are the units of volume in this application?</p></li>
</ol></p></subsection>

<subsection><title>Wrap-Up</title>
<p>In this Lesson, we worked on the following skills and goals related to polynomials:</p>
<p><ul>
<li><p>Compute products of polynomials</p></li>    
<li><p>Compute cubes of binomials</p></li>    
<li><p>Factor the sum or difference of cubes</p></li>  
<li><p>Use polynomials as models</p></li>
</ul></p>

<commentary audience="instructor"><title>Questions for Writing or Discussion</title>
<p><ol>
<li><p>Explain the difference between the expressions <m>(a+b)^3</m> and <m>a^3 + b^3</m>.</p></li>
<li><p>Compare the formulas for expanding <m>(a-b)^2</m> and <m>(a-b)^3</m>.</p></li>
<li><p>Explain why a cost function might have the shape of a cubic polynomial.</p></li>
<li><p>Explain how to find the surface area of a solid figure (such as a box or a cylinder).</p></li>
</ol></p></commentary>
</subsection>

